00:37:26,773 --> 00:37:28,764
You must miss her.

491
00:37:28,875 --> 00:37:31,844
Mmm, every day. You?

492
00:37:31,945 --> 00:37:35,972
Well, I didn't know your wife,
so, no, I can't say that I do.

493
00:37:36,082 --> 00:37:39,711
- [Chuckling]
- [All Laughing]

494
00:37:39,819 --> 00:37:43,220
Oh, finally,
a date with Lewis Feldman.

495
00:37:43,323 --> 00:37:45,223
What do you mean?

496
00:37:45,325 --> 00:37:48,021
He's had his eye on you
since he got here.

497
00:37:48,127 --> 00:37:50,687
- That's ridiculous. He has not.
- [Chuckles]

498
00:37:50,797 --> 00:37:54,528
Anyway, it's not a date.
I'm just helping him with his laundry.

499
00:37:54,634 --> 00:37:57,797
Why? What do you think dates look
like around here, bungee jumping?

500
00:37:57,904 --> 00:38:00,065
Believe me, it's a date.

501
00:38:02,242 --> 00:38:04,210
[Amy]
At least she's gone.

502
00:38:04,310 --> 00:38:07,006
Where'd she go to anyway?

503
00:38:08,515 --> 00:38:12,281
I don't know. My dad's, I guess.

504
00:38:12,385 --> 00:38:16,685
Well, that's good. Gives Sydelle
one more thing to complain about.

505
00:38:20,193 --> 00:38:22,593
Which one are you crying about—

506
00:38:22,695 --> 00:38:25,562
the predatory prick
or the shit-for-brains tramp?

507
00:38:26,866 --> 00:38:30,427
'Cause neither one deserves your tears.

508
00:38:30,537 --> 00:38:32,437
[Sobs]

509
00:38:32,539 --> 00:38:35,235
You know, Amy...

510
00:38:35,341 --> 00:38:37,309
I'm sure you're right...

511
00:38:39,412 --> 00:38:42,313
[Sobs]

512
00:38:42,415 --> 00:38:45,942
But sometimes I wish you'd just say...

513
00:38:46,052 --> 00:38:48,179
"Boy, that sucks...

514
00:38:48,288 --> 00:38:52,247
and I'm really sorry
it happened to you."

515
00:38:56,596 --> 00:38:59,827
- Do you have them for every high holiday?
- [Chuckling] Yeah.

516
00:38:59,933 --> 00:39:03,266
The Passover one says,
"What makes this tuchis unlike any other?"

517
00:39:03,369 --> 00:39:05,701
- [Laughs, Mouthing Words]
- My son, the joker.

518
00:39:05,805 --> 00:39:09,366
Thinks it makes up for the fact
that I don't see him on the holidays.

519
00:39:09,475 --> 00:39:12,069
- They go to her parents.
- Well, at least he's married.

520
00:39:12,178 --> 00:39:15,978
- My son— 55, still single.
- Gay?

521
00:39:16,082 --> 00:39:18,983
I wish. Immature.

522
00:39:19,085 --> 00:39:21,315
Ella, tell me about your family.

523
00:39:21,421 --> 00:39:24,686
Well, my husband Ira
was in real estate.

524
00:39:24,791 --> 00:39:26,759
Died three years ago. Cancer.

525
00:39:26,859 --> 00:39:30,295
- [Chuckles]
- That's funny?

526
00:39:30,396 --> 00:39:33,365
No, it's the way we do that—
the dead spouse intro.

527
00:39:33,466 --> 00:39:35,457
Name, rank, when did he die, how.

528
00:39:35,568 --> 00:39:37,661
But not the specifics.

529
00:39:37,770 --> 00:39:40,671
Cancer's okay,
but no one ever says "lung cancer."

530
00:39:40,773 --> 00:39:42,798
Or, God forbid, "prostate cancer."

531
00:39:42,909 --> 00:39:45,469
How 'bout you? Have any kids?

532
00:39:45,578 --> 00:39:48,069
[Chuckling Awkwardly]
No.

533
00:39:49,349 --> 00:39:51,977
No, I don't have any children.

534
00:39:52,085 --> 00:39:56,852
[Bell Tolling]

535
00:40:00,960 --> 00:40:05,920
- [Woman] Rufus? Is that Rufus?
- [Barking]

536
00:40:06,032 --> 00:40:08,865
Uh, is Shirley back
from Europe already?

537
00:40:08,968 --> 00:40:11,664
Ooh, I thought she— I thought she
was boarding Rufus for another month.

538
00:40:11,771 --> 00:40:13,671
She is. Yeah.

539
00:40:13,773 --> 00:40:18,210
I just... walk... Rufus.

540
00:40:18,311 --> 00:40:20,745
- Oh, you're with the Elegant Paw.
- No. No, I'm—

541
00:40:20,847 --> 00:40:22,747
- Hi, Carol.
- Hey, Carol.

542
00:40:22,849 --> 00:40:24,783
- Hi.
- Good girl, Molly.

543
00:40:24,884 --> 00:40:28,684
- I'm... freelance. A... freelance dog-walker.
- Oh, I see.

544
00:40:28,788 --> 00:40:32,189
Yeah, I work for kennels,
with kennels, and, uh...

545
00:40:32,291 --> 00:40:34,725
with— for individuals... too.

546
00:40:34,827 --> 00:40:37,159
- She's just what we need.
- Absolutely.

547
00:40:37,263 --> 00:40:40,892
- How much do you charge?
- [Laughs]

548
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,730
Jesus! You saved my ass.

549
00:40:43,836 --> 00:40:47,795
- Where did you find him?
- Oh, just... wandering around Rittenhouse.

550
00:40:47,907 --> 00:40:51,741
You know, I give this girl a job.
She seems normal.

551
00:40:51,844 --> 00:40:55,041
Next thing I know,
she's taken off with this dog.

552
00:40:55,148 --> 00:40:59,778
You can imagine, something like this gets out,
and I'm out of business.

553
00:40:59,886 --> 00:41:04,789
So, how does 200 sound for a reward?
Fair enough?

554
00:41:04,891 --> 00:41:07,485
- I don't want a reward.
- What are you, a saint?

555
00:41:07,593 --> 00:41:09,424
No.
[Chuckles]

556
00:41:09,529 --> 00:41:12,259
Uh, I was thinking...
maybe instead of a reward...

557
00:41:12,365 --> 00:41:15,061
you could offer your clients
my dog-walking services.

558
00:41:15,168 --> 00:41:17,534
Exclusively.

559
00:41:17,637 --> 00:41:20,868
We could split the proceeds.

560
00:41:51,471 --> 00:41:54,497
- Not so much as the Winnebago he left her.
- [Phone Ringing]

561
00:41:54,607 --> 00:41:56,939
- [Laughing]
- Oh, it's horrible!

562
00:41:57,043 --> 00:42:01,070
You won't be laughing when
you're eating government cheese.

563
00:42:01,180 --> 00:42:03,080
Hello.

564
00:42:04,550 --> 00:42:06,984
- Hello?
- [Maggie] Is this Ella Hirsch?

565
00:42:07,086 --> 00:42:08,986
Yes, it is.

566
00:42:09,088 --> 00:42:13,616
Did you have a daughter named Caroline?

567
00:42:13,726 --> 00:42:15,921
Yes.

568
00:42:30,710 --> 00:42:34,771
[Ella]
So, are you on vacation, or—

569
00:42:38,551 --> 00:42:40,451
Yeah.

570
00:42:40,553 --> 00:42:44,580
Mmm. Well, we've been
having wonderful weather.

571
00:42:50,062 --> 00:42:52,030
I'm so glad you called.

572
00:42:55,735 --> 00:42:57,703
I'm so glad you're here.

573
00:43:21,727 --> 00:43:24,560
[Indistinct TVNoise]

574
00:43:24,664 --> 00:43:27,724
Mrs. Lefkowitz, this is
my granddaughter Maggie Feller.

575
00:43:30,002 --> 00:43:33,028
- Hello.
- Hi.

576
00:43:33,139 --> 00:43:37,041
Well, you must be starving.
I can, uh, fix you something to eat—

577
00:43:37,143 --> 00:43:38,770
No, that's— I'm fine.

578
00:43:38,878 --> 00:43:41,676
I just, uh—

579
00:43:41,781 --> 00:43:46,741
- I'm really tired.
- Oh. Well, let me show you the guest room.

580
00:43:46,853 --> 00:43:50,152
Um, it's right through here.
Uh, this is the bathroom.

581
00:43:50,256 --> 00:43:53,919
And I'll put out clean towels
and, uh, a washcloth.

582
00:43:54,026 --> 00:43:56,494
The bed's made up...

583
00:43:56,596 --> 00:43:59,258
and there are, um,
extra blankets in the closet.

584
00:44:01,200 --> 00:44:05,136
- Is my grandfather around?
- Oh. No.

585
00:44:05,238 --> 00:44:08,765
No, Ira passed away
over three years ago.

586
00:44:10,409 --> 00:44:13,003
So, you'll call me
if you need anything?

587
00:44:13,112 --> 00:44:15,239
Yeah.

588
00:44:24,290 --> 00:44:26,190
[Sighs]

589
00:44:31,464 --> 00:44:34,695
Hey, you said you didn't have children.

590
00:44:34,800 --> 00:44:37,530
I said I don't have children.

591
00:44:37,637 --> 00:44:40,731
I had a daughter.

592
00:44:40,840 --> 00:44:43,035
Her name was Caroline.
She died.

593
00:44:43,142 --> 00:44:44,939
What was she like?

594
00:44:47,313 --> 00:44:51,977
Well, she was—
she was exactly like that.

595
00:44:52,084 --> 00:44:54,382
Same eyes, same skin...

596
00:44:54,487 --> 00:44:56,614
same face— identical.

597
00:44:59,158 --> 00:45:02,321
But she had, um, health problems.

598
00:45:02,428 --> 00:45:05,864
- She had mental health problems.
- Tsk.

599
00:45:05,965 --> 00:45:08,195
Well, how'd she die?

600
00:45:13,039 --> 00:45:14,939
Car accident.

601
00:45:17,076 --> 00:45:19,271
A leave of absence? Why?

602
00:45:19,378 --> 00:45:21,972
I'm just—
I'm not happy at that firm.

603
00:45:22,081 --> 00:45:24,242
So instead you'll be walking dogs.

604
00:45:24,350 --> 00:45:27,683
And running errands, and—
I think it'll be fun.

605
00:45:29,388 --> 00:45:31,913
Are you okay?

606
00:45:32,024 --> 00:45:33,992
You're not having—

607
00:45:35,194 --> 00:45:37,924
- What?
- [Sighs]

608
00:45:38,030 --> 00:45:42,967
If you ever want to talk to someone,
Rose, I'll pay for it.

609
00:45:43,069 --> 00:45:46,300
No questions asked.
If you're ever feeling—

610
00:45:46,405 --> 00:45:49,101
[Chuckles]
Crazy?

611
00:45:49,208 --> 00:45:52,439
I'm not the one
you should be worried about.

612
00:45:52,545 --> 00:45:55,878
How is Maggie?

613
00:45:55,982 --> 00:45:58,507
- You haven't seen her?
- No, she's still with you, isn't she?

614
00:45:58,617 --> 00:46:03,611
Oh, yeah, she is. She's fine.

615
00:46:03,723 --> 00:46:06,283
- Thanks for the coffee.
- All right. See you soon?

616
00:46:06,392 --> 00:46:08,292
Yeah.

617
00:46:12,832 --> 00:46:14,959
[Beeping]

618
00:46:18,137 --> 00:46:20,935
[Ringing]

619
00:46:21,040 --> 00:46:24,032
[Female Electronic Voice] The number
you have called is no longer in service.

620
00:46:24,143 --> 00:46:26,236
If you feel you have reached
this recording—

621
00:46:28,481 --> 00:46:30,381
[Yawns]

622
00:46:31,650 --> 00:46:33,550
Hmm.

623
00:46:40,793 --> 00:46:43,023
Well, good morning.

624
00:46:43,129 --> 00:46:45,029
Did you sleep well?

625
00:46:45,131 --> 00:46:47,031
Fine, thanks.

626
00:46:47,133 --> 00:46:50,660
I have English muffins here.
I can make you any kind of eggs you'd like.

627
00:46:50,770 --> 00:46:53,739
- I don't eat breakfast.
- Oh.

628
00:46:53,839 --> 00:46:55,807
I drink coffee.

629
00:46:57,376 --> 00:47:01,506
So, my goodness. This is a surprise.

630
00:47:01,614 --> 00:47:03,582
Such a lovely surprise.

631
00:47:05,051 --> 00:47:07,019
After all this time.

632
00:47:08,554 --> 00:47:11,455
- Yeah, what's up with that?
- I beg your pardon?

633
00:47:11,557 --> 00:47:16,358
Well, were you always out of the picture,
or just after Mom died?

634
00:47:16,462 --> 00:47:21,593
Oh, your grandfather and I were never out
of the— I mean, we were always there.

635
00:47:21,700 --> 00:47:23,600
We—

636
00:47:23,702 --> 00:47:27,331
And even after your mom died, I wrote.

637
00:47:27,440 --> 00:47:30,534
Birthday cards, every year.
And I never heard back.

638
00:47:30,643 --> 00:47:33,578
Yeah, I know. You wrote
for a while. I just found them.

639
00:47:33,679 --> 00:47:36,443
What do you mean, "just"?

640
00:47:36,549 --> 00:47:40,610
I guess they got waylaid.
Thanks for the money.

641
00:47:40,719 --> 00:47:43,984
You're telling me that your father
never gave you my cards?

642
00:47:44,090 --> 00:47:46,251
Mm-mmm.

643
00:47:46,358 --> 00:47:48,826
What must you have thought?

644
00:47:50,463 --> 00:47:53,261
I thought you both were dead.

645
00:47:57,937 --> 00:48:00,064
Does this place have a pool?

646
00:48:00,172 --> 00:48:03,073
- Oh! Sorry.
- Whoa.

647
00:48:03,175 --> 00:48:05,735
Whoa! Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa! Whoa!

648
00:48:05,845 --> 00:48:08,177
Come on.

649
00:48:08,280 --> 00:48:11,374
- [Chattering]
- Hey, check this out.

650
00:48:11,484 --> 00:48:14,783
[Reggae PopMan Singing]

651
00:48:18,090 --> 00:48:20,354
Hey.

652
00:48:22,761 --> 00:48:25,127
Where'd she come from?

653
00:48:43,115 --> 00:48:45,140
Hi, sweetheart.

654
00:48:57,796 --> 00:48:59,764
Come on, come on.

655
00:49:10,409 --> 00:49:12,536
[Panting]

656
00:49:12,645 --> 00:49:14,943
[Barking]

657
00:49:20,753 --> 00:49:22,653
Come on. Keep playing.

658
00:49:25,824 --> 00:49:28,088
Rose! Rose Feller!

659
00:49:28,194 --> 00:49:30,219
[Chuckles]
Oh, Stein.

660
00:49:30,329 --> 00:49:32,422
How are you?

661
00:49:32,531 --> 00:49:36,023
Man, you look great.
Not sick at all.

662
00:49:36,135 --> 00:49:37,864
Why would I look sick?

663
00:49:37,970 --> 00:49:40,404
Oh.

664
00:49:40,506 --> 00:49:43,498
- That's one of the rumors.
- There are rumors?

665
00:49:45,044 --> 00:49:47,672
[Bell Tolls]

666
00:49:47,780 --> 00:49:50,340
How 'bout that? Lunchtime.

667
00:49:50,449 --> 00:49:53,748
- Hey, how does, uh— How does Japanese sound?
- I'm not hungry, Stein.

668
00:49:53,852 --> 00:49:57,117
Oh, there's no such thing
as not hungry for sushi. Come on.

669
00:49:57,223 --> 00:49:59,885
We'll bill it to one of your old clients.

670
00:49:59,992 --> 00:50:01,892
Uh, thank you.
You eat everything?

671
00:50:01,994 --> 00:50:03,962
- What do you think?
- Okay.

672
00:50:04,063 --> 00:50:08,261
- Um, two orders of uni, one masago.
- Mm-hmm.

673
00:50:08,367 --> 00:50:10,198
- Uh, two tako.
- Okay.

674
00:50:10,302 --> 00:50:12,099
- Two hamachi.
- Mm-hmm.

675
00:50:12,204 --> 00:50:16,231
Then also that cod thing. It was a special
once, but it's not on the menu anymore.

676
00:50:16,342 --> 00:50:18,310
- You know what I'm talking about.
- Tara.

677
00:50:18,410 --> 00:50:20,310
- Yes!
- Okay. Thank you.

678
00:50:20,412 --> 00:50:23,404
- Okay, thank you.
- Thanks.

679
00:50:23,515 --> 00:50:25,745
- You just ordered for me.
- Yes.

680
00:50:25,851 --> 00:50:28,149
- What am I, 12?
- Uh, I'm an expert orderer.

681
00:50:28,254 --> 00:50:30,119
- It's a gift.
- Is it?

682
00:50:30,222 --> 00:50:32,850
Absolutely.

683
00:50:32,958 --> 00:50:36,052
What was the last
great restaurant you went to?

684
00:50:36,161 --> 00:50:39,892
- I took my sister to Le Bec Fin.
- Uh-huh.

685
00:50:39,999 --> 00:50:45,130
And you both got the... snapper,
right?

686
00:50:45,237 --> 00:50:47,296
Close. I got the snapper.

687
00:50:47,406 --> 00:50:51,172
- She got three rum and Cokes
and the sommelier's phone number.
- [Laughs] Okay.

688
00:50:51,277 --> 00:50:55,270
Well, I'll take you there,
and we'll get...

689
00:50:55,381 --> 00:50:59,647
the foie gras
with Roquefort-stuffed fig...

690
00:50:59,752 --> 00:51:02,277
Scottish wood pigeon with cabbage...

691
00:51:02,388 --> 00:51:04,913
and porcini cassoulet.

692
00:51:06,725 --> 00:51:08,693
And the chocolate mousse...

693
00:51:08,794 --> 00:51:11,354
with raspberries
and hazelnut macaroon.

694
00:51:11,463 --> 00:51:14,432
You'll want to eat with me
for the rest of your life.

695
00:51:18,937 --> 00:51:20,666
- Ah.
- Here you go.

696
00:51:20,773 --> 00:51:23,037
- Mmm.
- I know.

697
00:51:23,142 --> 00:51:24,973
- The special, tara.
- Thank you.

698
00:51:25,077 --> 00:51:26,977
Enjoy.

699
00:51:28,247 --> 00:51:31,307
So— [Clears Throat]
What are the other rumors?

700
00:51:31,417 --> 00:51:33,544
Ah. Um—

701
00:51:33,652 --> 00:51:36,712
Rumor one: Mysterious illness.

702
00:51:36,822 --> 00:51:39,882
Rumor two: Head-hunted
by Pepper and Hamilton.

703
00:51:42,795 --> 00:51:45,025
Here. Try some of this.

704
00:51:45,130 --> 00:51:48,361
- Rumor three?
- Um, soy?

705
00:51:48,467 --> 00:51:50,662
Oh, come on.
What's rumor three?

706
00:51:55,474 --> 00:51:58,238
Affair with a partner gone bad.

707
00:51:58,344 --> 00:52:00,812
[Laughs]

708
00:52:04,817 --> 00:52:06,717
Don't worry.

709
00:52:06,819 --> 00:52:09,083
Most people are betting on lupus.

710
00:52:16,295 --> 00:52:19,423
Here.
Wasabi makes everything better.

711
00:52:24,169 --> 00:52:27,229
- So, uh, what time Friday?
- Friday?

712
00:52:27,339 --> 00:52:29,239
Dinner.

713
00:52:29,341 --> 00:52:33,243
Oh, look, Simon, this was— this was
really nice, but, um, I don't think—

714
00:52:33,345 --> 00:52:35,210
7:00 it is.

715
00:52:38,217 --> 00:52:40,117
Thank you.

716
00:52:46,358 --> 00:52:48,826
Mmm. That smells good.
What is that?

717
00:52:48,927 --> 00:52:50,895
That's braised veal.

718
00:52:54,833 --> 00:52:56,858
- Shit.
- [Drink Fizzing]

719
00:52:56,969 --> 00:52:59,130
There's a paper towel on the counter.

720
00:53:05,711 --> 00:53:07,838
Out of curiosity...

721
00:53:07,946 --> 00:53:11,040
how long is this vacation of yours
going to last?

722
00:53:11,150 --> 00:53:14,381
How come you don't have
any pictures of my mom around?

723
00:53:14,486 --> 00:53:17,421
Don't you like thinking about her?

724
00:53:17,523 --> 00:53:20,492
I don't need to have a picture
to think about my daughter.

725
00:53:29,067 --> 00:53:32,468
You put out pictures,
people ask questions.

726
00:53:32,571 --> 00:53:35,597
They expect you to tell 'em everything,
and I don't do that.

727
00:53:35,707 --> 00:53:38,175
'Cause Mom was sick?

728
00:53:38,277 --> 00:53:40,575
Because she's gone.

729
00:53:42,848 --> 00:53:44,907
Is that why you pulled away from us?

730
00:53:45,017 --> 00:53:47,485
So that you didn't have to talk
about her with us either?

731
00:53:47,586 --> 00:53:50,578
I didn't pull away. I was pushed.

732
00:53:53,025 --> 00:53:54,925
No, listen.

733
00:53:55,027 --> 00:53:58,656
I'm not the one who didn't pass along
the letters. That was your father.

734
00:53:58,764 --> 00:54:00,698
I'm not the one
