The first time you got laid.

976
01:11:20,671 --> 01:11:22,571
You had to tell someone that.

977
01:11:23,708 --> 01:11:26,040
It was my wedding night.
It was assumed.

978
01:11:26,143 --> 01:11:30,045
You missed out on one of the all-time
greatest conversations in life.

979
01:11:31,315 --> 01:11:33,283
Who'd you tell?

980
01:11:35,019 --> 01:11:36,987
Rose.

981
01:11:37,088 --> 01:11:39,386
Well, maybe if I'd had a sister.

982
01:11:39,490 --> 01:11:41,958
Even when you were so small...

983
01:11:42,059 --> 01:11:44,584
you had a bond
that I'd never had with anyone.

984
01:11:45,730 --> 01:11:48,062
You still close like that?

985
01:11:49,667 --> 01:11:51,567
Sure.

986
01:11:51,669 --> 01:11:54,433
- You don't talk about her.
- What do you want to hear?

987
01:11:56,641 --> 01:11:59,576
We're totally fine. We're-We're tight.
We're thick as thieves.

988
01:11:59,677 --> 01:12:03,135
Let's ask her down.
I'd like to know her too.

989
01:12:03,247 --> 01:12:06,182
You know, I doubt she would come.

990
01:12:06,284 --> 01:12:09,378
She's, like, really busy.
She's a lawyer.

991
01:12:09,487 --> 01:12:11,055
- No kidding. What kind?
- The really busy kind.

992
01:12:11,055 --> 01:12:13,114
- No kidding. What kind?
- The really busy kind.

993
01:12:14,625 --> 01:12:16,957
[Amy] What do you do
once they've all peed?

994
01:12:17,061 --> 01:12:20,394
[Rose] Hmm. Give 'em a brush.
Take 'em all home.

995
01:12:20,498 --> 01:12:22,966
Make sure they have water to drink.

996
01:12:25,202 --> 01:12:28,729
- After that.
- Then I'm done.

997
01:12:30,207 --> 01:12:33,973
- So what do you do?
- Whatever.

998
01:12:34,078 --> 01:12:38,981
- Shop for food, cook for my boyfriend.
- I know his name.

999
01:12:39,083 --> 01:12:43,076
I know, but I've never really had a real,
live, grown-up boyfriend before...

1000
01:12:43,187 --> 01:12:46,179
and I'm gonna use the word
as often as I can.

1001
01:12:46,290 --> 01:12:49,157
All right, first of all,
he's not grown up.

1002
01:12:49,260 --> 01:12:51,160
None of them are.

1003
01:12:51,262 --> 01:12:55,858
You know, there's a consistency
to your cynicism which is truly beautiful.

1004
01:12:55,967 --> 01:12:58,094
Hmm. Just don't be surprised...

1005
01:12:58,202 --> 01:13:01,399
if he turns out to be...
less than perfect.

1006
01:13:01,505 --> 01:13:03,973
And don't be surprised if he doesn't.

1007
01:13:06,544 --> 01:13:08,512
- I gotta go.
- Good-bye.

1008
01:13:08,613 --> 01:13:10,513
- Have fun.
- I'll call you.

1009
01:13:10,615 --> 01:13:11,843
All right.

1010
01:13:12,416 --> 01:13:16,011
[Old Man] You sound too pretty,
Maggie, to be cleaning bedpans.

1011
01:13:16,120 --> 01:13:18,588
You're right. I am.

1012
01:13:18,689 --> 01:13:22,125
I have a grandson, a doctor over in Tampa.
I should introduce you.

1013
01:13:22,226 --> 01:13:25,320
- [Chuckles] You don't want to do that.
- Are you bad news?

1014
01:13:25,429 --> 01:13:29,593
[Sighs] Well, you know,
I don't mean to be, but yeah.

1015
01:13:29,700 --> 01:13:33,158
Well, since you're not gonna
marry my grandson...

1016
01:13:33,270 --> 01:13:35,500
you might as well read to me.

1017
01:13:41,278 --> 01:13:43,439
- I'm kind of a slow reader.
- Perfect.

1018
01:13:43,547 --> 01:13:46,345
I'm a slow listener.

1019
01:13:55,960 --> 01:13:59,862
"The... art... of...

1020
01:14:01,966 --> 01:14:03,900
Iosing"—

1021
01:14:05,469 --> 01:14:08,836
- You know, I should just get back to work.
- What is it, dyslexia?

1022
01:14:08,939 --> 01:14:11,339
- What are you, a teacher?
- Professor.

1023
01:14:11,442 --> 01:14:15,071
Retired.
Just take your time, Maggie.

1024
01:14:15,179 --> 01:14:18,342
Listen to the words
as you're about to say them.

1025
01:14:18,449 --> 01:14:20,917
Nine times out of 10,
you'll hear a mistake coming...

1026
01:14:21,018 --> 01:14:23,486
and you'll correct it
before you make it.

1027
01:14:23,587 --> 01:14:27,489
Then again, you might make
a total ass of yourself.

1028
01:14:43,808 --> 01:14:46,436
Oh, come on.

1029
01:14:46,544 --> 01:14:49,513
Poetry's supposed to be slow.

1030
01:15:01,559 --> 01:15:04,084
"The... art...

1031
01:15:04,195 --> 01:15:07,187
"of... losing...

1032
01:15:07,298 --> 01:15:11,701
"isn't hard to...

1033
01:15:11,802 --> 01:15:13,702
"master.

1034
01:15:16,240 --> 01:15:19,004
"So many... things...

1035
01:15:19,110 --> 01:15:21,635
"may... seem... file—

1036
01:15:21,746 --> 01:15:25,477
"seem... filled...

1037
01:15:25,583 --> 01:15:28,416
"with the... intent...

1038
01:15:28,519 --> 01:15:31,511
"to be... lost...

1039
01:15:31,622 --> 01:15:34,716
"that their... loss...

1040
01:15:34,825 --> 01:15:36,725
"is no...

1041
01:15:41,932 --> 01:15:43,832
"disaster.

1042
01:15:47,605 --> 01:15:51,041
"Lose... some—

1043
01:15:52,576 --> 01:15:56,137
"something every day.

1044
01:15:56,247 --> 01:15:59,910
'Ac-Accept the fluster...

1045
01:16:00,017 --> 01:16:02,781
"of lost door keys.

1046
01:16:04,388 --> 01:16:08,085
"I lost... two cities...

1047
01:16:08,192 --> 01:16:10,922
"two... rivers...

1048
01:16:11,028 --> 01:16:15,021
"a... contin—

1049
01:16:15,132 --> 01:16:17,032
"continen— continent.

1050
01:16:18,135 --> 01:16:20,763
"I... miss them...

1051
01:16:20,871 --> 01:16:25,604
"but it wasn't a... disaster.

1052
01:16:26,710 --> 01:16:29,611
"Even... losing you...

1053
01:16:29,713 --> 01:16:32,204
"the joking voice...

1054
01:16:32,316 --> 01:16:34,511
"a... gesture...

1055
01:16:35,886 --> 01:16:38,514
"I love...

1056
01:16:38,622 --> 01:16:43,457
"I... shan't have lied.

1057
01:16:43,561 --> 01:16:47,053
"It's... evi-evident...

1058
01:16:47,164 --> 01:16:50,531
"the... art... oflosing's...

1059
01:16:50,634 --> 01:16:53,865
"not too hard to master...

1060
01:16:55,139 --> 01:16:58,540
"though it look—
though it may look...

1061
01:16:58,642 --> 01:17:02,237
"like— (Write it.!)—

1062
01:17:02,346 --> 01:17:04,246
"like...

1063
01:17:04,348 --> 01:17:06,782
disaster."

1064
01:17:13,157 --> 01:17:15,955
Well, what do you think?

1065
01:17:16,060 --> 01:17:19,621
[Sighs]
Good.

1066
01:17:19,730 --> 01:17:23,257
Unacceptable answer.
What's the poem about?

1067
01:17:24,635 --> 01:17:27,103
- I don't know.
- Yes, you do. What's it about?

1068
01:17:30,808 --> 01:17:32,742
- Losing?
- What?

1069
01:17:35,980 --> 01:17:37,880
- Love?
- Ah.

1070
01:17:37,982 --> 01:17:40,314
And how about that?

1071
01:17:41,585 --> 01:17:44,383
Is the love lost already?

1072
01:17:44,488 --> 01:17:47,753
Is Bishop writing about it
as a possibility, a probability?

1073
01:17:47,858 --> 01:17:49,758
What?

1074
01:17:51,395 --> 01:17:53,295
Well...

1075
01:17:54,798 --> 01:17:57,266
in the beginning,
she's talking about...

1076
01:17:57,368 --> 01:18:01,998
Iosing real things, like keys.

1077
01:18:03,374 --> 01:18:07,333
And then she— she gets, like—

1078
01:18:07,444 --> 01:18:09,344
she lost a continent.

1079
01:18:09,446 --> 01:18:12,540
- She's getting grandiose.
- Yeah.

1080
01:18:12,650 --> 01:18:16,450
And the way she says it is like—
like it doesn't matter.

1081
01:18:16,553 --> 01:18:18,453
Ah.

1082
01:18:18,555 --> 01:18:21,490
Her tone—
would you call it detached?

1083
01:18:23,394 --> 01:18:26,420
I think she wants
to sound detached.

1084
01:18:26,530 --> 01:18:30,626
You know,
she wants to... sound...

1085
01:18:30,734 --> 01:18:32,634
like it doesn't matter...

1086
01:18:32,736 --> 01:18:35,432
'cause she knows, deep down...

1087
01:18:35,539 --> 01:18:38,099
how bad it's gonna feel to lose.

1088
01:18:38,208 --> 01:18:40,108
Lose what?

1089
01:18:41,278 --> 01:18:43,678
Or whom?

1090
01:18:45,049 --> 01:18:47,017
Is it a lover?

1091
01:18:51,488 --> 01:18:53,388
No.

1092
01:18:58,429 --> 01:19:00,397
It's a friend.

1093
01:19:03,567 --> 01:19:05,535
A-plus.

1094
01:19:06,737 --> 01:19:09,535
Smart girl.

1095
01:19:26,390 --> 01:19:28,290
[Sighs]

1096
01:19:30,127 --> 01:19:33,392
[Sydelle]
Oh, what a—a comfortable home.

1097
01:19:33,497 --> 01:19:35,397
It's very, uh, lived in.

1098
01:19:35,499 --> 01:19:37,558
Well, what can I get you?

1099
01:19:37,668 --> 01:19:41,502
- I'll have a white wine, and he'll have the same.
- Oh, good.

1100
01:19:41,605 --> 01:19:46,133
Why don't you just make yourself at home,
and I'll be right back.

1101
01:19:46,243 --> 01:19:48,143
- Hey, Dad!
- Hello, sweetie.

1102
01:19:48,245 --> 01:19:50,145
- Oh!
- Where's Maggie?

1103
01:19:50,247 --> 01:19:53,739
- Oh, not here.
- Oh, thank God. We don't need
her drama tonight.

1104
01:19:53,851 --> 01:19:57,753
- Why isn't she here? Is something wrong?
- No, we just had a fight.

1105
01:19:57,855 --> 01:20:01,416
- About what?
- Can we talk about this later?

1106
01:20:01,525 --> 01:20:04,756
Yes. Bad enough she monopolizes
the evening when she's here.

1107
01:20:04,862 --> 01:20:07,490
Oh, let me see that ring.

1108
01:20:09,500 --> 01:20:12,799
[Gasps]
Oh, wow. Look at that.

1109
01:20:15,806 --> 01:20:19,503
Rose tells me you have a daughter
as well, Sydelle.

1110
01:20:19,610 --> 01:20:21,601
My Marcia? You'll meet her.

1111
01:20:21,712 --> 01:20:25,170
You'll love her. Everyone does.
My Marcia's a decorator.

1112
01:20:25,282 --> 01:20:26,772
[Mrs. Stein]
Really?

1113
01:20:26,884 --> 01:20:30,081
[Sydelle]
She's an absolute genius in her work.

1114
01:20:30,187 --> 01:20:32,178
I'd like to say a few words.

1115
01:20:32,289 --> 01:20:36,055
Please. To Rose and Simon.

1116
01:20:36,160 --> 01:20:38,594
We're all blessed to be a part
of your happiness.

1117
01:20:38,695 --> 01:20:41,789
Your love bonds
notjust your two hearts...

1118
01:20:41,899 --> 01:20:44,697
but the hearts of two families.

1119
01:20:44,802 --> 01:20:46,861
- Mazel tov!
- [All] Mazel tov!

1120
01:20:46,970 --> 01:20:49,200
- Mazel tov!
- Thanks, Dad.

1121
01:20:49,306 --> 01:20:51,831
- That went okay.
- Yeah.

1122
01:20:51,942 --> 01:20:53,910
Where's Maggie?

1123
01:20:54,011 --> 01:20:56,479
Uh, it's hard to say.
She moves around a lot.

1124
01:20:56,580 --> 01:20:59,708
Well, I want to meet her eventually,
you know? She's your sister.

1125
01:20:59,817 --> 01:21:02,718
- I want to know her.
- You will.

1126
01:21:02,820 --> 01:21:05,050
What was the fight about?

1127
01:21:05,155 --> 01:21:07,123
Mmm. Girl stuff.

1128
01:21:14,398 --> 01:21:16,298
Oh, shit.

1129
01:21:17,835 --> 01:21:19,769
Oh.!

1130
01:21:19,870 --> 01:21:23,237
I should have used fresh vegetables
instead of frozen.

1131
01:21:23,340 --> 01:21:25,638
[Ella]
I don't think so. They were great.

1132
01:21:25,742 --> 01:21:28,336
- Really delicious. They were good.
- Really?

1133
01:21:28,445 --> 01:21:30,345
Yes.

1134
01:21:30,447 --> 01:21:34,315
- So, have you heard from Rose?
- No.

1135
01:21:34,418 --> 01:21:37,080
- So she hasn't gotten back to you.
- About what?

1136
01:21:37,187 --> 01:21:39,678
You were going
to invite her down, Maggie.

1137
01:21:39,790 --> 01:21:41,758
I don't know
where you got that idea.

1138
01:21:41,859 --> 01:21:44,987
Maggie,
I specifically asked you to.

1139
01:21:45,095 --> 01:21:48,929
So? Just because you specifically asked
doesn't mean I'm going to.

1140
01:21:49,032 --> 01:21:52,399
You shouldn't smoke.
You have a family history of lung cancer.

1141
01:21:52,503 --> 01:21:54,596
I have a family history
of car wrecks too.

1142
01:21:54,705 --> 01:21:57,105
Does that mean I shouldn't drive?

1143
01:21:57,207 --> 01:21:59,505
- That is not funny.
- It wasn't supposed to be.

1144
01:21:59,610 --> 01:22:01,874
All right, what is the problem
between you and Rose?

1145
01:22:01,979 --> 01:22:05,278
- Why don't you want her to visit?
- Why do you?

1146
01:22:05,382 --> 01:22:07,942
I mean,
am I not good enough for you?

1147
01:22:08,051 --> 01:22:10,645
This has nothing to do with you.

1148
01:22:10,754 --> 01:22:13,780
She's my daughter's daughter,
and I want to get to know her too.

1149
01:22:20,664 --> 01:22:22,632
[Water Running]

1150
01:22:30,641 --> 01:22:32,632
What was Caroline like with you girls?

1151
01:22:32,743 --> 01:22:35,644
I mean, as a mom,
how do you remember her?

1152
01:22:35,746 --> 01:22:37,907
Why don't you ask Rose?

1153
01:22:38,015 --> 01:22:41,348
Maggie, please grow up.

1154
01:22:47,457 --> 01:22:49,357
She was special.

1155
01:22:49,459 --> 01:22:51,859
Different than the other moms.

1156
01:22:51,962 --> 01:22:53,930
She used to surprise us.

1157
01:22:56,733 --> 01:22:59,566
One time I opened up
my lunch box...

1158
01:23:00,671 --> 01:23:03,902
and there was a tiara inside.

1159
01:23:04,007 --> 01:23:06,532
A tiara. With your sandwich?

1160
01:23:06,643 --> 01:23:08,543
Instead of a sandwich.

1161
01:23:10,414 --> 01:23:12,882
What was she like as a daughter?

1162
01:23:14,117 --> 01:23:16,017
No tiaras.

1163
01:23:18,755 --> 01:23:21,781
But I loved her so much.

1164
01:23:25,329 --> 01:23:28,958
But loving her in the right way
was difficult, for me, anyway.

1165
01:23:29,066 --> 01:23:31,762
I didn't know there was
a right way and a wrong way.

1166
01:23:31,868 --> 01:23:33,836
Neither did I.

1167
01:23:35,005 --> 01:23:37,701
I had ideas—

1168
01:23:37,808 --> 01:23:41,608
I had unwelcomed ideas
about how to keep her safe.

1169
01:23:41,712 --> 01:23:43,976
Like?

1170
01:23:44,081 --> 01:23:47,380
Like, I thought she should have been
on her medication all the time.

1171
01:23:47,484 --> 01:23:49,816
I thought that her relationship
with your father...

1172
01:23:49,920 --> 01:23:52,252
was far too passionate
for her to handle.

1173
01:23:52,356 --> 01:23:54,324
And as far as children
were concerned...

1174
01:23:54,424 --> 01:23:57,552
she was in no condition,
no condition at all.

1175
01:23:57,661 --> 01:24:00,494
So you wish she never had me.

1176
01:24:03,333 --> 01:24:05,301
You know what I wish, Maggie?

1177
01:24:07,271 --> 01:24:09,899
I wish I'd kept my big mouth
shut long enough...

1178
01:24:10,007 --> 01:24:12,441
to hear what she wanted
out of life.

1179
01:24:14,537 --> 01:24:17,233
[Chattering In Distance]

1180
01:24:19,809 --> 01:24:21,709
[Chuckles]

1181
01:24:21,811 --> 01:24:25,110
[Sydelle]
There she is! There's the bride!

1182
01:24:26,849 --> 01:24:28,407
Be strong.

1183
01:24:30,053 --> 01:24:34,547
Stay right here.
I'll get your corsage.

1184
01:24:34,657 --> 01:24:37,490
Corsage? What is this, a prom?

1185
01:24:37,594 --> 01:24:39,721
- Ladies?
- Ah, thank you.

1186
01:24:41,998 --> 01:24:45,490
- Who are these people?
- I have no idea.

1187
01:24:45,602 --> 01:24:49,060
- Except for my Marcia.
- Hello!

1188
01:24:49,172 --> 01:24:52,141
Hey, you're not sticking around...

1189
01:24:52,241 --> 01:24:56,007
to watch me ooh and ahh
over a Mixmaster Deluxe?

1190
01:24:56,112 --> 01:24:58,580
It's good of you
to let Sydelle do this.

1191
01:24:58,681 --> 01:25:02,173
- Oh, like gale force winds could stop her.
- Go easy on her.

1192
01:25:02,285 --> 01:25:05,516
- Marcia's giving her a very hard time these days.
- Oh, what's she doing?

1193
01:25:05,622 --> 01:25:08,182
Decorating in last year's colors?

1194
01:25:08,291 --> 01:25:10,816
She joined Jews forJesus.

1195
01:25:15,632 --> 01:25:17,793
Yoo-hoo! Ladies, it's time...

1196
01:25:17,900 --> 01:25:21,700
for the entertainment portion
of our soiree.

1197
01:25:21,804 --> 01:25:25,205
Uh, everyone get where you can see.
Anita, Jackie, come on.

1198
01:25:25,308 --> 01:25:28,175
Scoot. [Giggles]
Here we go.

1199
01:25:28,277 --> 01:25:30,177
[Women]
Aw!

1200
01:25:30,279 --> 01:25:33,112
We, who know Rose,
are so thrilled...

1201
01:25:33,216 --> 01:25:36,708
that this day has finally arrived.

1202
01:25:36,819 --> 01:25:40,346
- Aw.
- There was a time we had our doubts.

1203
01:25:40,456 --> 01:25:42,219
[Laughter]

1204
01:25:42,325 --> 01:25:44,316
Oh, my goodness.

1205
01:25:44,427 --> 01:25:48,523
All that time spent with her nose
buried in her book.

1206
01:25:48,631 --> 01:25:50,690
- [Laughter]
- [Woman] Oh, bookworm.

1207
01:25:50,800 --> 01:25:56,534
Of course, there were romances,
but for some reason or other, nothing stuck.

1208
01:25:56,639 --> 01:25:59,870
- Oh!
- [Woman] A little heavy.

1209
01:25:59,976 --> 01:26:05,380
- Oh. One thing Rose always
had was a great appetite.
- [Laughter]

1210
01:26:05,481 --> 01:26:07,540
For life!

1211
01:26:14,290 --> 01:26:16,190
[Groans]

1212
01:26:16,292 --> 01:26:18,192
Oh, God!

1213
01:26:18,294 --> 01:26:21,195
Why would anyone want to marry me?
I'm disgusting!

1214
01:26:21,297 --> 01:26:25,028
The only disgusting person here
is your stepmother. She's hideous.

1215
01:26:25,134 --> 01:26:28,399
So why is she giving me this party?
She hates me.

1216
01:26:28,504 --> 01:26:30,972
Someone else should do it—
someone who l-loves me...

1217
01:26:31,074 --> 01:26:33,338
someone who can look at me
and say...

1218
01:26:33,443 --> 01:26:36,742
"All of this is nothing more
than the happiness you deserve."

1219
01:26:36,846 --> 01:26:38,905
