1456
01:45:26,575 --> 01:45:28,941
Hello, Rose!

1457
01:45:29,044 --> 01:45:32,309
[Man] Good, Lydia. A good stretch.
That's it. And left.

1458
01:45:32,414 --> 01:45:34,314
Looking good, Mrs. Klein.

1459
01:45:34,416 --> 01:45:36,316
- Hi, Maggie.
- Hi, ladies.

1460
01:45:36,418 --> 01:45:38,818
Hi!

1461
01:45:38,920 --> 01:45:41,855
I call these guys The Bench.
They're all former lawyers.

1462
01:45:41,957 --> 01:45:45,586
- Gentlemen! Hey.
- Hi, Maggie.

1463
01:45:45,694 --> 01:45:48,788
This is my sister, Rose.
She's a lawyer, too, from Philadelphia.

1464
01:45:48,897 --> 01:45:51,866
- Which firm?
- Uh, actually, no firm right now.

1465
01:45:51,967 --> 01:45:55,459
I'm just... taking some time off.

1466
01:45:55,570 --> 01:45:58,038
- Me too.
- [Laughing]

1467
01:46:05,247 --> 01:46:08,341
- What are you doing, Ella?
- Sit down, girls.

1468
01:46:08,450 --> 01:46:13,012
I've got some things here
I thought you might like to see.

1469
01:46:13,121 --> 01:46:16,056
- Whoa.
- Oh, God.

1470
01:46:16,157 --> 01:46:18,057
- [Chuckles]
- Look at you.

1471
01:46:18,159 --> 01:46:20,719
- These are great.
- Hey, look. Our old living room.

1472
01:46:20,829 --> 01:46:22,922
Mm-hmm.

1473
01:46:23,031 --> 01:46:24,828
Oh, God.

1474
01:46:24,933 --> 01:46:28,164
Could Mom have been any prettier?

1475
01:46:28,270 --> 01:46:30,932
Oh, you look exactly like her.
Doesn't she?

1476
01:46:31,039 --> 01:46:34,475
- I wonder if there's a picture of Honey Bun.
- That'd be pretty impossible.

1477
01:46:34,576 --> 01:46:36,203
- Who's Honey Bun?
- Our dog.

1478
01:46:36,311 --> 01:46:38,006
- You had a dog?
- For one day.

1479
01:46:38,113 --> 01:46:40,946
The greatest day.

1480
01:46:41,049 --> 01:46:43,847
Mom woke us up really early.
It was a school day. It was still dark out.

1481
01:46:43,952 --> 01:46:45,852
It was winter.

1482
01:46:45,954 --> 01:46:49,856
And she put us in our best party dresses and
dragged us down to the kitchen, which was—

1483
01:46:49,958 --> 01:46:52,449
- A mess.
- Covered, every counter, in fudge.

1484
01:46:52,560 --> 01:46:54,357
She'd been up all night making it.

1485
01:46:54,462 --> 01:46:58,091
We loaded it into the car,
and she drove us right past school...

1486
01:46:58,199 --> 01:47:00,167
straight up to New York,
to Lord & Taylor.

1487
01:47:00,268 --> 01:47:02,736
Which was closed, because we got there
at 8:00 in the morning.

1488
01:47:02,837 --> 01:47:05,806
- That's right, and we hung out in the car.
- Eating fudge for breakfast.

1489
01:47:05,907 --> 01:47:08,967
Mom had heard about Mrs. Fields.
You know, the cookie lady?

1490
01:47:09,077 --> 01:47:12,308
And she figured that her fudge
was just as good as those cookies, so—

1491
01:47:12,414 --> 01:47:14,382
So she was gonna make a fortune.

1492
01:47:14,482 --> 01:47:19,283
When it finally opened, we went in
and, oh, God, she was so beautiful.

1493
01:47:19,387 --> 01:47:22,914
- She was wearing this long, velvety gown.
- At 8:00 in the morning?

1494
01:47:23,024 --> 01:47:25,754
Well, by this time it was 10:00.

1495
01:47:25,860 --> 01:47:28,954
I guess she talked to some of the store people
about the fudge, but I don't remember.

1496
01:47:29,064 --> 01:47:31,862
Mmm, she spilled it,
all over the jewelry counter.

1497
01:47:31,967 --> 01:47:36,495
- There was a guy who just kind of looked at her.
- I don't remember a guy.

1498
01:47:36,604 --> 01:47:39,471
There was a guy,
and he looked at her.

1499
01:47:41,176 --> 01:47:44,839
Anyway, Mom said that we could
each get one present.

1500
01:47:44,946 --> 01:47:47,506
- And you got—
- A Nancy Drew book.

1501
01:47:47,615 --> 01:47:50,948
I asked for a puppy. And she got it!

1502
01:47:51,052 --> 01:47:54,749
[Sighs] He was so cute.
I named him Honey Bun.

1503
01:47:54,856 --> 01:47:57,791
Why'd you only have it for one day?

1504
01:47:57,892 --> 01:48:00,793
- I guess Dad thought it was a bad idea.
- [Ella] Why?

1505
01:48:00,895 --> 01:48:04,126
I don't know. I think he thought
I was too young.

1506
01:48:04,232 --> 01:48:06,291
No. He was just mad.

1507
01:48:06,401 --> 01:48:11,134
- About a dog?
- No, about the whole day.

1508
01:48:11,239 --> 01:48:15,300
He didn't have any idea where we were,
and school had called.

1509
01:48:15,410 --> 01:48:18,140
- Oh.
- Really?

1510
01:48:18,246 --> 01:48:22,205
Yeah. He was really panicked
and really, really mad at her.

1511
01:48:22,317 --> 01:48:24,285
They had a huge fight.

1512
01:48:24,386 --> 01:48:27,378
I don't remember a fight.

1513
01:48:27,489 --> 01:48:30,515
You were in your room
with a record playing.

1514
01:48:30,625 --> 01:48:32,684
- I was?
- Yeah.

1515
01:48:32,794 --> 01:48:36,958
I put you in there and turned the music on
so you wouldn't hear them.

1516
01:48:37,065 --> 01:48:40,694
[Ella]
Why? What were they saying?

1517
01:48:44,506 --> 01:48:46,474
He was saying...

1518
01:48:47,675 --> 01:48:50,143
she was unfit.

1519
01:48:50,245 --> 01:48:53,373
That's the word he used.

1520
01:48:53,481 --> 01:48:57,781
He said he was gonna... send her away.
Put her away. Something.

1521
01:48:57,886 --> 01:49:01,378
- He kept saying "away."
- Mmm. And her?

1522
01:49:01,489 --> 01:49:04,083
"Oh, there's nothing wrong with me.
I'm a good mother."

1523
01:49:04,192 --> 01:49:07,355
He'd say, "away,"
and she'd say, "I'm their mother!"

1524
01:49:07,462 --> 01:49:10,659
So he was—he was gonna
have her hospitalized.

1525
01:49:12,934 --> 01:49:14,834
Yeah.

1526
01:49:22,811 --> 01:49:24,711
Oh, God. The poor guy.

1527
01:49:27,882 --> 01:49:29,782
When exactly was this?

1528
01:49:29,884 --> 01:49:31,852
November 3.

1529
01:49:34,355 --> 01:49:37,381
No. No, it wasn't.
It was, like, months before that.

1530
01:49:37,492 --> 01:49:39,392
It was two days.

1531
01:49:39,494 --> 01:49:42,930
It was Tuesday,
and she died that Thursday.

1532
01:49:53,274 --> 01:49:55,640
It was on purpose, wasn't it?

1533
01:49:58,513 --> 01:50:00,743
The car, the tree.

1534
01:50:02,350 --> 01:50:06,252
[Water Running]

1535
01:50:06,354 --> 01:50:08,822
Was it even raining that night?

1536
01:50:12,360 --> 01:50:14,328
You were so little.

1537
01:50:16,431 --> 01:50:20,834
How do you tell a six-year-old
her mom left by choice?

1538
01:50:27,242 --> 01:50:29,267
Who told you?

1539
01:50:33,148 --> 01:50:35,582
No one.

1540
01:50:44,159 --> 01:50:48,186
- Oh, God. Why can't I just stay mad at you?
- [Sniffling]

1541
01:50:48,296 --> 01:50:51,857
'Cause we're a pair,
like Sonny and Cher.

1542
01:50:51,966 --> 01:50:54,059
They split up.

1543
01:50:54,169 --> 01:50:57,138
- But they remained quite close.
- [Chuckles]

1544
01:51:08,283 --> 01:51:10,513
I'm not engaged anymore.

1545
01:51:14,455 --> 01:51:16,355
Simon dumped me.

1546
01:51:22,730 --> 01:51:25,460
Why are you still wearing the ring?

1547
01:51:27,135 --> 01:51:29,865
[Crying]
I like how it feels.

1548
01:51:33,841 --> 01:51:37,402
- Do you know his name?
- Simon Stein.

1549
01:51:37,512 --> 01:51:39,412
- Doctor?
- Lawyer.

1550
01:51:39,514 --> 01:51:42,142
- Oh. Nice.
- So you call information—

1551
01:51:42,250 --> 01:51:46,414
"Simon Stein in Philly"—
Get his number, make a call.

1552
01:51:46,521 --> 01:51:48,421
And say what?

1553
01:51:48,523 --> 01:51:51,356
"Hey, jerk, you broke my sister's heart.
Come down here and make it right."

1554
01:51:51,459 --> 01:51:53,359
Maybe not that, word-for-word.

1555
01:51:53,461 --> 01:51:57,158
- He broke up with her.
He's not gonna want to come.
- Well, you don't know that.

1556
01:51:57,265 --> 01:51:59,199
Men can be very confused.

1557
01:51:59,300 --> 01:52:03,464
Yeah, too many options—
be an astronaut, be a playboy.

1558
01:52:03,571 --> 01:52:06,404
Often a man needs help
making the right choice.

1559
01:52:06,507 --> 01:52:09,874
Yeah, how am I supposed to help him?
He doesn't even know me.

1560
01:52:09,978 --> 01:52:11,878
He knows your sister.

1561
01:52:11,980 --> 01:52:14,744
And loves her, or he wouldn't have
proposed in the first place.

1562
01:52:14,849 --> 01:52:20,048
- So?
- So, what if he learns she was in trouble?

1563
01:52:20,154 --> 01:52:22,179
Or sick.

1564
01:52:22,290 --> 01:52:24,190
Or pregnant.

1565
01:52:25,360 --> 01:52:27,260
Dora!

1566
01:52:27,362 --> 01:52:30,160
Don't look so shocked,
Miss Comes-To-Florida-

1567
01:52:30,265 --> 01:52:32,733
To-Milk-Your-Grandmother-
For-All-She's-Worth.

1568
01:52:32,834 --> 01:52:35,325
We know all about you.

1569
01:52:43,578 --> 01:52:46,672
- So, dog walking.
- Oh, don't worry about it.

1570
01:52:46,781 --> 01:52:51,241
It's not forever. It's just to keep me busy
till I figure out my next move.

1571
01:52:51,352 --> 01:52:54,321
Well, when you figure it out,
I hope you'll let me know.

1572
01:52:54,422 --> 01:52:58,153
You know, down here, if you don't have
successful grandchildren to brag about...

1573
01:52:58,259 --> 01:53:00,250
you're screwed.

1574
01:53:00,361 --> 01:53:00,928
What are we reading today?
A little Emily Dick? A little—

1575
01:53:00,928 --> 01:53:03,396
What are we reading today?
A little Emily Dick? A little—

1576
01:53:19,380 --> 01:53:21,280
[Footsteps Approaching]

1577
01:53:25,953 --> 01:53:27,921
Did they move him?

1578
01:53:30,858 --> 01:53:32,758
He died.

1579
01:53:32,860 --> 01:53:34,760
This morning.

1580
01:53:42,437 --> 01:53:44,337
Bummer.

1581
01:53:46,741 --> 01:53:50,302
- Were you on duty?
- No, l-I don't work here.

1582
01:53:50,411 --> 01:53:52,311
This is his chart.

1583
01:53:52,413 --> 01:53:55,712
You're his grandson, the doctor.

1584
01:53:57,552 --> 01:53:59,452
Who are you?

1585
01:54:01,656 --> 01:54:05,615
Um, nobody.
L-I just— I read to him sometimes.

1586
01:54:08,763 --> 01:54:10,731
You're Maggie.

1587
01:54:13,167 --> 01:54:15,135
He talked about me?

1588
01:54:17,672 --> 01:54:19,572
Just a little.

1589
01:54:31,519 --> 01:54:33,987
[DistantJazz]

1590
01:54:40,361 --> 01:54:42,659
- [Jazz]
- [Chattering]

1591
01:54:55,977 --> 01:54:57,877
- Hey.
- Hey.

1592
01:54:57,979 --> 01:55:00,004
Who's Fred Astaire?

1593
01:55:03,217 --> 01:55:05,412
That's Lewis.

1594
01:55:07,555 --> 01:55:10,023
You're a very good dancer, Lewis.

1595
01:55:11,392 --> 01:55:14,020
Know what else I'm good at?

1596
01:55:14,128 --> 01:55:16,028
[Gasps]

1597
01:55:16,130 --> 01:55:17,722
[Gasps]

1598
01:55:27,408 --> 01:55:29,399
Simon.

1599
01:55:29,510 --> 01:55:31,808
What are you doing here?

1600
01:55:31,913 --> 01:55:34,313
I came as soon as your sister called.

1601
01:55:40,721 --> 01:55:42,689
Should you be drinking?

1602
01:55:45,593 --> 01:55:48,391
[Piano Plays Gentle Melody]

1603
01:55:54,402 --> 01:55:56,870
[No Audible Dialogue]

1604
01:55:58,573 --> 01:56:00,598
- So you're not pregnant.
- No. [Confused Chuckle]

1605
01:56:00,708 --> 01:56:03,643
- Never were.
- Don't you think I would tell you
if I were pregnant?

1606
01:56:03,744 --> 01:56:06,269
I don't know.
You know, I hope so, but, frankly...

1607
01:56:06,380 --> 01:56:09,440
there were a lot of things
you weren't telling me back there.

1608
01:56:09,550 --> 01:56:13,111
[Gentle Melody Continues]

1609
01:56:13,221 --> 01:56:17,920
I promise, anything I kept from you
had nothing to do with us.

1610
01:56:18,025 --> 01:56:20,823
It was about Maggie.

1611
01:56:20,928 --> 01:56:24,762
[Sighs] I was protecting her
because that's what I do.

1612
01:56:24,866 --> 01:56:29,826
You need to know this, because
if by some insane stroke of fate...

1613
01:56:29,937 --> 01:56:32,030
you do decide to marry me...

1614
01:56:32,139 --> 01:56:35,233
she will make your life a living hell.

1615
01:56:35,343 --> 01:56:37,311
You'll be begging me
to kick her out...

1616
01:56:37,411 --> 01:56:39,538
commit her, kill her, anything.

1617
01:56:39,647 --> 01:56:41,638
And I'll want to...

1618
01:56:41,749 --> 01:56:43,717
but I never will.

1619
01:56:45,753 --> 01:56:48,881
[Voice Cracks]
Because without her...

1620
01:56:48,990 --> 01:56:50,958
I don't make sense.

1621
01:56:55,796 --> 01:56:59,698
You look good.
You look like you.

1622
01:57:10,478 --> 01:57:13,572
- I can't believe I'm in Florida.
- [Laughs]

1623
01:57:16,851 --> 01:57:18,751
- [Ella] You'll come back?
- Yes, I promise.

1624
01:57:18,853 --> 01:57:20,753
- Now, you hold her to it.
- I will.

1625
01:57:20,855 --> 01:57:23,756
Okay, don't buy a wedding dress.
It's gonna be my gift to you.

1626
01:57:23,858 --> 01:57:26,156
[Laughs]
No way.

1627
01:57:26,260 --> 01:57:29,821
You'll have me in some
hootchie-mama monstrosity.

1628
01:57:29,931 --> 01:57:33,367
Look, I'm good at this. Trust me.

1629
01:57:40,041 --> 01:57:42,737
Are you sure this is the right place?

1630
01:57:42,843 --> 01:57:46,074
[Man] Only oneJerk Hut
in Philadelphia, ma'am.

1631
01:57:47,448 --> 01:57:49,348
[Man SingingReggae]

1632
01:57:52,186 --> 01:57:54,086
[Door Opens]

1633
01:58:01,529 --> 01:58:03,394
Michael.

1634
01:58:03,497 --> 01:58:05,124
Ella.

1635
01:58:07,768 --> 01:58:09,895
This is my friend, Lewis Feldman.

1636
01:58:10,004 --> 01:58:13,940
- Lewis, this is Michael Feller, father of the bride.
- Pleased to meet you.

1637
01:58:14,041 --> 01:58:16,976
Welcome. Rose will be
so glad you're here.

1638
01:58:17,078 --> 01:58:18,978
Ella!

1639
01:58:21,549 --> 01:58:23,073
- [Giggles Excitedly]
- [Both] Oh.

1640
01:58:23,184 --> 01:58:25,084
I'm so glad you're here.

1641
01:58:25,186 --> 01:58:27,086
- Are you excited?
- [Rose] Yeah.

1642
01:58:27,188 --> 01:58:28,883
[Ella]
Yes? Perfect.

1643
01:58:28,990 --> 01:58:31,959
[Maggie] She gets really mad
if you leave the lid off the ice cream.

1644
01:58:32,059 --> 01:58:33,959
[Simon]
I know.

1645
01:58:34,061 --> 01:58:36,723
- Don't even think about using her toothbrush.
- Mm-hmm.

1646
01:58:36,831 --> 01:58:39,231
- And she hates the look of raw chicken.
- I know.

1647
01:58:39,333 --> 01:58:41,665
And if she starts humming
"Hava Nagila"...

1648
01:58:41,769 --> 01:58:44,260
she's, like, really, really mad—
like, mad.

1649
01:58:44,372 --> 01:58:47,933
Mag— Maggie, I know. I know her.

1650
01:58:48,042 --> 01:58:50,909
[Chuckles Lightly]

1651
01:58:51,012 --> 01:58:53,344
- Okay.
- Okay.

1652
01:58:53,447 --> 01:58:55,278
Mm-hmm.

1653
01:58:55,383 --> 01:58:57,851
I wore them in 1952.

1654
01:59:00,621 --> 01:59:02,885
- Old.
- But not to you.

1655
01:59:02,990 --> 01:59:06,153
- Right.
- And if I didn't give them to you?

1656
01:59:06,260 --> 01:59:09,354
- Borrowed.
- Mm-hmm. And look at the flowers.

1657
01:59:09,463 --> 01:59:11,590
- Blue.
- Yeah.

1658
01:59:13,100 --> 01:59:15,466
So, uh, Simon—

1659
01:59:15,569 --> 01:59:18,436
[Man SingingReggae]

1660
01:59:18,539 --> 01:59:21,201
I'll be back in a few minutes.

1661
01:59:31,852 --> 01:59:34,320
[Ella]
They are so lovely.

1662
01:59:34,422 --> 01:59:37,585
You should be very proud.

1663
01:59:39,727 --> 01:59:42,195
I'm afraid I can't take much credit.

1664
01:59:44,432 --> 01:59:47,094
Well, it's not always easy
taking care of yourself...

1665
01:59:47,201 --> 01:59:50,637
and someone else
at the same time.

1666
01:59:54,909 --> 01:59:57,844
I owe you an apology, Ella.

1667
02:00:01,782 --> 02:00:03,682
Many, in fact.

1668
02:00:06,887 --> 02:00:09,822
I owe quite a few myself.

1669
02:00:12,026 --> 02:00:13,926
[Rabbi]
You'll be entering from—

1670
02:00:14,028 --> 02:00:17,225
Oh, yeah, just along here
and, um, down these stairs.

1671
02:00:17,331 --> 02:00:20,596
- And will someone be escorting you?
- My dad.

1672
02:00:20,701 --> 02:00:22,896
- That's nice.
- Dad.

1673
02:00:25,339 --> 02:00:28,331
[Rhythmic Drums Continue]

1674
02:00:28,442 --> 02:00:30,501
[Piano "Here Comes the Bride"]

1675
02:01:02,910 --> 02:01:04,810
[Song Ends]

1676
02:01:04,912 --> 02:01:07,642
- Thanks, Dad.
- Thanks, Michael.

1677
02:01:20,728 --> 02:01:24,095
And now, a very special moment.

1678
02:01:24,198 --> 02:01:26,428
Young lady?

1679
02:01:26,534 --> 02:01:31,164
Uh, this isn't in the program,
'cause it's a surprise.

1680
02:01:31,272 --> 02:01:33,900
I surprise Rose a lot.

1681
02:01:35,843 --> 02:01:37,777
Uh, usually, she hates it.

1682
02:01:37,878 --> 02:01:40,176
I think, or I hope...

1683
02:01:40,281 --> 02:01:42,613
that she likes this.

1684
02:01:46,086 --> 02:01:50,022
It's a poem by e.e. Cummings.

1685
02:01:50,124 --> 02:01:52,524
For you.

1686
02:02:00,301 --> 02:02:03,202
"I carry your heart with me.

1687
02:02:03,304 --> 02:02:05,636
"I carry it in my heart.

1688
02:02:05,739 --> 02:02:07,866
"I am never without it.

1689
02:02:07,975 --> 02:02:11,206
"Anywhere I go, you go, my dear.

1690
02:02:11,312 --> 02:02:13,940
"And whatever is done by only me...

1691
02:02:14,048 --> 02:02:17,108
"is your doing, my darling.

1692
02:02:18,285 --> 02:02:19,946
"I fear no fate...

